lsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cailly","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Liam.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Raghailligh</b> ‘son of <i>Raghailleach</i>’. Compare   Crawley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Crawley","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places called Crawley, for example in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Sussex, and Oxfordshire, named with Old English <i>crāwe</i> ‘crow’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare   Crowley  .","Irish (Louth): in Ireland, this is generally the English name in 1 above, but it may also have been adopted for <b>McCrawley</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Raghallaigh</b> ‘son of <i>Raghallach</i>’, also Anglicized as <b>Magreely</b>."]},{"name":"Crilley","meanings":["Irish (Derry): variant of   Crilly  ."]},{"name":"Kriley","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Irish   Crilly  ."]},{"name":"Grilley","meanings":["Possibly an altered form of Irish   Crilly  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Cailly was born in 1280, in Buckenham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Adam Cailley, was 29 and her mother, Emma Tattershall, was 24. She married Roger de Clifton in 1305, in Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in 1368, in her hometown, at the age of 88, and was buried in Buckenham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom."},